Predictive Modeling of Trial Outcomes Using Neural Activity and Stimulus Contrasts in Mouse Visual Cortex

06/06/2023

Abstract:

This project aims to develop a predictive model for trial outcome using neural activity data and stimulus contrasts. The datasets the model is based off of consists of recordings from the visual cortex of mice during decision-making tasks. By leveraging the relationship between neural activity patterns and stimulus information, the model accurately predicts trial outcomes. The findings contribute to our understanding of how neural activity relates to decision-making processes and have potential implications for various fields, including neuroscience and artificial intelligence.

Section 1 Introduction:

This project aims to build a predictive model to predict the outcome or feedback type of each trial using the neural activity data along with the stimuli (the left and right contrasts). The data set used in this project is from a study by Steinmetz et al.(2019) and involves 10 mice and 39 experimental sessions. The mice were presented with visual stimuli of varying contrast levels and had to make decisions using a wheel, with feedback in the form of rewards or penalties provided based on their decisions. Spike train data, representing neuron firing, was recorded from the mices visual cortex. Our model is based on 18 sessions from four mice: Cori, Forssmann, Hench, and Lederberg. We took these sessions and identify shared patterns and/or session-specific differences to improve prediction performance.

We aim to first understand the neural activity patterns associated with visual stimulus processing and gain insights into underlying mechanisms. The feedback outcomes are as follows:

  • When left contrast > right contrast, success (1) if turning the wheel to the right and failure (-1) otherwise.
  • When right contrast > left contrast, success (1) if turning the wheel to the left and failure (-1) otherwise.
  • When both left and right contrasts are zero, success (1) if holding the wheel still and failure (-1) otherwise.
  • When left and right contrasts are equal but non-zero, left or right will be randomly chosen (50%) as the correct choice.

The activity of the neurons in the mices visual cortex was recorded during the trials and made available in the form of spike trains, which are collections of timestamps corresponding to neuron firing. In this project, we focus specifically on Mouse, ContrastLeft, and Brain Area to build our Feedback prediction model.

Part 2. Exploratory data analysis. In this part, we will explore the features of the data sets in order to build our prediction model. In particular, we would like to (i) describe the data structures across sessions (e.g., number of neurons, number of trials, stimuli conditions, feedback types), (ii) explore the neural activities during each trial, (iii) explore the changes across trials, and (iv) explore homogeneity and heterogeneity across sessions and mice.

# Function to calculate average spike counts by area
average_spike_area <- function(i_trial, session_data) {
  spikes_trial <- session_data$spks[[i_trial]]
  area <- session_data$brain_area
  spike_counts <- apply(spikes_trial, 1, sum)
  average_spikes_tapply <- tapply(spike_counts, area, mean)
  return(average_spikes_tapply)
}

We also see that spike counts vary very much by brain region and trial, with some trials having significantly more average spike counts than others.

Part (iii) explore the spk changes across trials

library(ggplot2)

session_data <- session
spike_trains <- session$spks

for (i in 8) {
  session_data <- session[[i]]
  
  cat("Session:", i, "\n")
  
  num_trials <- length(session_data$feedback_type)
  
  trial_data <- data.frame(Trial = numeric(num_trials),
                           Spike_Count = numeric(num_trials),
                           stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  
  for (j in 1:num_trials) {
    spike_train <- session_data$spks[[j]]
    spike_count <- apply(spike_train, 1, sum)
    total_spike_count <- sum(spike_count)
    trial_data$Trial[j] <- j
    trial_data$Spike_Count[j] <- total_spike_count
  }
  
  cat("\nTrial Data:\n")
  print(head(trial_data))
  
  p <- ggplot(trial_data, aes(x = Trial, y = Spike_Count)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "lightblue") +
    labs(x = "Trial", y = "Spike Count", 
         title = paste("Spike Count per Trial - Session", i)) +
    theme_minimal()
  
  print(p)
}

Part (iv) explore homogeneity and heterogeneity across sessions and mice

suppressWarnings({

  library(data.table)

  mouse_groups <- c(rep("Cori", 3), rep("Forssmann", 4), rep("Hench", 4), rep("Lederberg", length(session) - 11))
  all_spike_trains <- list()
  for (i in 1:length(session)) {
    session_data <- session[[i]]
  
   session_spike_trains <- list()
  
   for (j in 1:length(session_data$spks)) {
     spike_train <- session_data$spks[[j]]
    
     # Add the spike train data to the session_spike_trains list
     session_spike_trains[[j]] <- spike_train
    }
  
    # Add the session_spike_trains list to the all_spike_trains list
   all_spike_trains[[i]] <- session_spike_trains
  }

# Calculate the mean spike count for each session and trial
  mean_spike_counts <- sapply(all_spike_trains, function(session_spikes) {
    sapply(session_spikes, function(spike_train) mean(rowSums(spike_train)))
  })

  session_mean_spike_counts <- sapply(mean_spike_counts, mean)

  mouse_mean_spike_counts <- tapply(unlist(mean_spike_counts), rep(1:length(session), sapply(mean_spike_counts, length)), mean)

  overall_mean_spike_count <- mean(unlist(mean_spike_counts))

  within_session_heterogeneity <- sapply(mean_spike_counts, function(session_counts) {
    sum((session_counts - session_mean_spike_counts)^2)
  })

# Calculate the between-session heterogeneity
  between_session_heterogeneity <- sum((session_mean_spike_counts - overall_mean_spike_count)^2)
# Create a vector to repeat mouse group names based on the number of trials
  mouse_groups_rep <- rep(mouse_groups, sapply(mean_spike_counts, length))
# Calculate the mouse-wise mean spike count
  mouse_mean_spike_counts <- tapply(unlist(mean_spike_counts), mouse_groups_rep, mean)
  overall_mean_spike_count <- mean(unlist(mean_spike_counts))
  between_mouse_heterogeneity <- sum((mouse_mean_spike_counts - overall_mean_spike_count)^2)

  cat("Within-Session Heterogeneity:\n")
  print(within_session_heterogeneity)
  cat("\nBetween-Session Heterogeneity:\n")
  print(between_session_heterogeneity)
  cat("\nBetween-Mouse Heterogeneity:\n")

Above is the code to explore general homogeneity and heterogeneity amongst the spikes accross sessions. Between-mouse heterogeneity is a measure of the variability in mean spike counts across different mice. Specifically, it represents the sum of squared differences between the mean spike counts of each mouse group and the overall mean spike count.

There is a lower value of between-mouse heterogeneity which suggests more similarity in the mean spike counts between mice, indicating a degree of consistency in neural spk activity patterns across the different mice.

There is a high Within-Session Heterogeneity, which indicates that there is significant variation in spike counts within each session. This suggests that the neural activity patterns during different trials within the same session are diverse and not consistent. This isnt super informative towards finding out which variables most impact feedback so lets take a closer look at the variables using ANOVA.

library(data.table)

# Create a data frame to store the variables of interest
data <- data.frame(Session = factor(),
                   Mouse = character(),
                   FeedbackType = numeric(),
                   ContrastLeft = numeric(),
                   ContrastRight = numeric(),
                   BrainArea = character(),
                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for (i in 1:18) {
  session_data <- session[[i]]
  num_trials <- length(session_data$feedback_type)
  
  for (j in 1:num_trials) {
    feedback_type <- session_data$feedback_type[j]
    contrast_left <- session_data$contrast_left[j]
    contrast_right <- session_data$contrast_right[j]
    
    # Determine the corresponding mouse and brain area based on the session index
    mouse <- ifelse(i %in% c(1, 2, 3), "Cori",
                    ifelse(i %in% c(4, 5, 6, 7), "Forssmann",
                           ifelse(i %in% c(8, 9, 10, 11), "Hench", "Lederberg")))
    
    brain_area <- session_data$brain_area[j]
    data <- rbind(data, data.frame(Session = i,
                                   Mouse = mouse,
                                   FeedbackType = feedback_type,
                                   ContrastLeft = contrast_left,
                                   ContrastRight = contrast_right,
                                   BrainArea = brain_area))
  }
  
}

data$Session=as.factor(data$Session)

result <- aov(FeedbackType ~ Session + Mouse + ContrastLeft + ContrastRight + BrainArea, data = data)

library(dplyr)

proportions <- data %>%

Here I define the test and training set and build a prediction model. The p argument specifies the proportion of data to be assigned to the training set (in this case, 80% for training and 20% for testing). The set.seed function is used to set a random seed for reproducibility.

The predicted probabilities are converted to binary class labels using the ifelse function. Values greater than 0.7 are assigned a class label of 1, indicating success, while values less than or equal to 0.7 are assigned a class label of 0, indicating failure.I am using p=0.8 rather than the usual p=0.7 in building the train_index because otherwise there would be some variables in the test set unaccounted for in the training data. As a reminder, I previously set the feedback values to be 0 and 1 rather than -1 and 1 to make it easier for me to calculate accuracy as a percentage.

Some other key insights include the sensitivity, also known as True Positive Rate or Recall, measures the proportion of actual positive cases correctly predicted as positive. In this case, the sensitivity is 0.12795, which is very low. One possible way to increase the sensitivity would be to raise the threshold value. Another key value is the specificity which is very high, at 0.92768. The specificity measures the proportion of actual negative cases correctly predicted as negative, and we have a pretty high specificity ratio.

Discussion

Based on the provided information, if we are solely considering accuracy as the criterion for selecting a model, the first model (threshold of 0.6) with an accuracy of 0.64 would be preferred over the second model with an accuracy of 0.555 (threshold of 0.63). The first model has a higher accuracy, indicating a higher proportion of correctly classified instances.

However, its important to note that accuracy alone may not provide a complete picture of model performance. Other metrics such as sensitivity, specificity, positive predictive value, and negative predictive value should also be taken into account. Additionally, the context and specific requirements of the application should be considered when choosing a model.

Upon comparing the additional performance metrics between the two models, we find that the second model has a higher sensitivity, indicating a better ability to correctly detect the positive cases, while the first model exhibits a higher specificity, suggesting a lower false positive rate. However, both models show relatively low positive predictive values, implying a significant number of false positives. In terms of negative predictive values, the second model performs slightly better. Considering the balanced accuracy, which considers both sensitivity and specificity, the second model has a slightly higher value. Overall, neither model demonstrates exceptional performance in terms of accuracy, sensitivity, or specificity. Thus, selecting the better model would require a more comprehensive analysis, considering the specific objectives, requirements, and trade-offs of the application.

However, for our purposes, I am considering accuracy as the criterion for selecting a model. Thus the first model (threshold of 0.6) with an accuracy of 64%, is the model I have selected for our general prediction purposes.
